         <abstract>
            <p>
               Using Néron's reduction theory and a method of Tate, we develop a procedure for calculating the local and global Néron-Tate height on an elliptic curve over the rationals. The procedure is illustrated by means of two examples of Silverman and is then applied to calculate the global Néron-Tate height of a series of rank-one curves of Bremner-Cassels and of a series of rank-two curves of Selmer. In the latter case, the regulator is also computed, and a conjecture of S. Lang is investigated numerically. In dealing with the arithmetic of elliptic curves $E$ over a global field $K$, the task arises of computing the Néron-Tate height on the group $E(K)$ of rational points of $E$ over $K$. Solving this task in an efficient manner is important, for instance, in view of calculations concerning the Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture (see [2]) or of the conjectures of Serge Lang [6]. The purpose of this note is to suggest a procedure for performing the necessary calculations. 
            </p>
          </abstract>
